{"title_page": "Gerpla", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}\n'''''Gerpla''''' is a 1952 Icelandic novel by [[Halld\u00f3r Laxness]] based on the Old Icelandic ''[[F\u00f3stbr\u00e6\u00f0ra saga]]''.<ref>\u00c1str\u00e1\u00f0ur Eysteinsson, '[https://scancan.net/eysteinsson_1_26.htm Is Halld\u00f3r Laxness the Author of ''F\u00f3stbr\u00e6\u00f0ra saga''? On the Author Function, Intertextuality, Translation, and a Modern Writer\u2019s Relationship with the Icelandic Sagas]', trans. by Julian Mendoza ''Scandinavian-Canadian Stuies/\u00c9tudes Scandinaves au Canada'', 26 (2019), 132-55.</ref>\n\n==Translations==\n* 1954. ''Gerpla''. Translated by Ingegerd Nyberg Fries. Stockholm: Litteraturfr\u00e4mjandet.\n* 1958. ''The Happy Warriors''. Translated by Katherine John. London: Methuen.\n* 1962. ''Gerpla: Hrdinsk\u00e1 s\u00e1ga''. Translated by Nina Neklanov\u00e1. Jiskry: Nov\u00e1 beletristick\u00e1 knihovna 37. Prague: Nakladatelstv\u00ed politick\u00e9 literatury.\n* 1977. ''Gerpla: Eine Heldensage''. Translated by Bruno Kress. Berlin: Aufbau.\n* 1988. ''Gerpla: S\u00e1ga o hrdinoch''. Translated by Jaroslav Ka\u0148a. Bratislava: Slovensk\u00fd spisovate\u013e.\n* 2016. ''Wayward Heroes''. Translated by Phillip Roughton. New York: Archipelago Books.\n\n==Further reading==\nSee Alec Shaw, '[https://scancan.net/shaw_1_26.htm \u201cThe lore of skalds, warrior ideals, and tales of ancient kings\u201d: A Bibliography on ''Gerpla'']', ''Scandinavian-Canadian Studies/\u00c9tudes scandinaves au Canada'', 26 (2019), 320\u201325, and other articles in the [https://scancan.net/master_vol_26.htm same issue of the journal].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{Iceland-stub}}\n{{Uncategorized stub|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}\n'''''Gerpla''''' is a 1952 Icelandic novel by [[Halld\u00f3r Laxness]] based on the Old Icelandic ''[[F\u00f3stbr\u00e6\u00f0ra saga]]''.<ref>\u00c1str\u00e1\u00f0ur Eysteinsson, '[https://scancan.net/eysteinsson_1_26.htm Is Halld\u00f3r Laxness the Author of ''F\u00f3stbr\u00e6\u00f0ra saga''? On the Author Function, Intertextuality, Translation, and a Modern Writer\u2019s Relationship with the Icelandic Sagas]', trans. by Julian Mendoza ''Scandinavian-Canadian Stuies/\u00c9tudes Scandinaves au Canada'', 26 (2019), 132-55.</ref>\n\n==Translations==\n* 1954. ''Gerpla''. Translated by Ingegerd Nyberg Fries. Stockholm: Litteraturfr\u00e4mjandet.\n* 1958. ''The Happy Warriors''. Translated by Katherine John. London: Methuen.\n* 1962. ''Gerpla: Hrdinsk\u00e1 s\u00e1ga''. Translated by Nina Neklanov\u00e1. Jiskry: Nov\u00e1 beletristick\u00e1 knihovna 37. Prague: Nakladatelstv\u00ed politick\u00e9 literatury.\n* 1977. ''Gerpla: Eine Heldensage''. Translated by Bruno Kress. Berlin: Aufbau.\n* 1988. ''Gerpla: S\u00e1ga o hrdinoch''. Translated by Jaroslav Ka\u0148a. Bratislava: Slovensk\u00fd spisovate\u013e.\n* 2016. ''Wayward Heroes''. Translated by Phillip Roughton. New York: Archipelago Books.\n\n==Further reading==\nSee Alec Shaw, '[https://scancan.net/shaw_1_26.htm \u201cThe lore of skalds, warrior ideals, and tales of ancient kings\u201d: A Bibliography on ''Gerpla'']', ''Scandinavian-Canadian Studies/\u00c9tudes scandinaves au Canada'', 26 (2019), 320-25, and other articles in the [https://scancan.net/master_vol_26.htm same issue of the journal].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Iceland-stub}}\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, addeduncategorisedtags,typo(s) fixed: 320-25 \u2192 320\u201325", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gerpla"}
{"title_page": "Trammel of Archimedes", "text_new": "[[File:Trammel of Archimedes Small White.gif|thumb|Trammel of Archimedes animated model.]]\n\nA '''trammel of Archimedes''' is a [[mechanism (engineering)|mechanism]] that generates the shape of an [[ellipse]].<ref>{{cite book |title=The Words of Mathematics |url=https://archive.org/details/wordsofmathemati0000schw |url-access=registration |last=Schwartzman |first=Steven |year=1996 |publisher=The [[Mathematical Association of America]] |isbn=0-88385-511-9}} ({{Google books|SRw4PevE4zUC|restricted online copy|page=223}})</ref> It consists of two shuttles which are confined (\"[[Wikt:trammel|trammelled]]\") to perpendicular channels or rails and a rod which is attached to the shuttles by pivots at fixed positions along the rod. \n\nAs the shuttles move back and forth, each along its channel, all points on the rod move in elliptical paths.  The motion of the rod is termed elliptical motion. The semi-axes ''a'' and ''b'' of the ellipses have lengths equal to the distances from the point on the rod to each of the two pivots. \n\nThe straight lines described by the pivots are special cases of an ellipse, where the length of one axis is twice the distance between the pivots and that of the other is zero. All points on a circle with a diameter defined by the two pivots reciprocate in such straight lines. This circle corresponds to the smaller circle in a [[Tusi_couple|Tusi couple]].\n\nThe point midway between the pivots orbits in a circle around the point where the channels cross. This circle is also a special case of an ellipse. Here the axes are of equal length. The diameter of the circle is equal to the distance between the pivots. The direction of travel around the orbit is opposite to the sense of rotation of the trammel. Thus, if a crank centred on the crossing point of the channels is used to engage the trammel at the midway point to drive it, the rotation of the crankpin and the trammel are equal and opposite, which in practical applications results in extra friction and accelerated wear. This is compounded by high forces owing to the short throw of the crank of only 1/4 the travel of the pivots.\n \nAn '''[[ellipsograph]]''' is a trammel of Archimedes intended to draw, cut, or machine ellipses, e.g. in [[wood]] or other sheet materials.  An ellipsograph has the appropriate instrument (pencil, knife, [[wood router|router]], etc.) attached to the rod.  Usually the [[distances]] ''a'' and ''b'' are adjustable, so that the size and shape of the ellipse can be varied.\n\nThe history of such ellipsographs is not certain, but they are believed to date back to [[Proclus]] and perhaps even to the time of [[Archimedes]].<ref name=AMM/>\n\nWooden versions of the trammel of Archimedes have been produced also as [[toy]]s or [[novelty item]]s, and sold under the name of '''[[Kentucky]] do-nothings''', '''nothing grinders''', '''do nothing machines''', or '''bullshit grinders'''.  In these toys  the drafting instrument is replaced by a [[Crank (mechanism)|crank]] handle, and the position of the sliding shuttles is usually fixed.\n\n== Mathematics ==\n{{Gallery\n |align=center\n |title=Concept\n |File:Archimedes Trammel.gif|Trammel of Archimedes as [[ellipsograph]].\n |File:Archimedes Trammel Diagram.png|Diagram]]\n |File:Archimedes_trammel_loci.svg|link={{filepath:Archimedes_trammel_loci.svg}}|Loci of some points along and beyond a trammel of Archimedes, the green \ncircle being the loci of its midpoint &ndash; [{{filepath:Archimedes_trammel_loci.svg}} in the SVG file,] move the pointer over the diagram to move the trammel\n |File:Trammel of Archimedes with three sliders.gif|Trammel of Archimedes with three sliders\n}}\nLet ''C'' be the outer end of the rod, and ''A'', ''B'' be the pivots of the sliders.  Let ''p'' and ''q'' be the distances from ''A'' to ''B'' and ''B'' to ''C'', respectively.  Let us assume that sliders ''A'' and ''B'' move along the ''y'' and ''x'' [[Cartesian coordinates|coordinate]] axes, respectively.  When the rod makes an angle ''\u03b8'' with the ''x''-axis, the coordinates of point ''C'' are given by\n\n:<math>x = (p+q) \\cos\\theta\\,</math>\n:<math>y = q \\sin\\theta\\,</math>\n\nThese are in the form of the standard parametric equations for an ellipse in canonical position. The further equation \n:<math>\\frac{x^2}{(p+q)^2}+ \\frac{y^2}{q^2}= 1</math>\nis immediate as well.\n\nThe trammel of Archimedes is an example of a [[four-bar linkage]] with two sliders and two pivots, and is special case of the more general oblique trammel. The axes constraining the pivots do not have to be perpendicular and the points ''A'', ''B'' and ''C'' can form a triangle. The resulting locus of ''C'' is still an ellipse.<ref name=AMM>{{cite journal|last=Wetzel|first=John E.|title=An Ancient Elliptic Locus|journal=[[American Mathematical Monthly]]|date=February 2010|volume=117|issue=2|pages=161\u2013167|jstor=10|doi=10.4169/000298910x476068}}</ref>\n\n{{Gallery\n |align=center\n |title=Examples of historical devices\n |File:SI ellipsograph crop.jpg|Wooden [[ellipsograph]] (ca. 1900) now at [[Smithsonian Institution Archives|Smithsonian]].\n |File:Bullshit grinder.jpg|Bullshit Grinder (ca. 1960)\n |Ellipse compass-MHS 614-IMG 3827-gradient.jpg|Ellipsograph on display at [[Mus\u00e9e d'histoire des sciences de la Ville de Gen\u00e8ve]].\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Beam compass]]\n* [[Bourke engine]]\n* [[John Farey Jr.]]\n* [[Tusi couple]]\n* [[Useless machine]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* J. W. Downs: ''Practical Conic Sections: The Geometric Properties of Ellipses, Parabolas and Hyperbolas''. Courier Dover 2003, {{ISBN|978-0-486-42876-5}}, pp.&nbsp;4\u20135 ({{Google books|pHxTQTiYkGYC|restricted online copy|page=4}})\n* I. I. Artobolevskii ''Mechanisms for the Generation of Plane Curves''. Pergamon Press 1964, {{ISBN|978-1483120003}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Trammel of Archimedes}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pid70tRkDJo Video of various trammel designs in action]\n*[http://www.woodweb.com/knowledge_base/A_Jig_for_Drawing_or_Cutting_Ellipses.html Cutting ellipses in wood]\n*[https://www.flickr.com/photos/sakraft1/3375895909/ Photo of a Kentucky Do-Nothing]\n*[http://www.instructables.com/id/Do_nothing_Machine/ Instructions] on how to build a Kentucky Do-Nothing\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GzQfQa8uv6M Video] of a Do-Nothing made from [[Lego]] bricks\n*[http://web.mat.bham.ac.uk/C.J.Sangwin/Publications/WonkyTrammel.pdf \"Wonky Trammel of Archimedes\"] An exploration of a generalized trammel.\n*[http://www.freepatentsonline.com/4306598.html US-Patent 4306598 for ellipse cutting guide allowing small ellipses]\n\n[[Category:Traditional toys]]\n[[Category:Mechanisms (engineering)]]\n[[Category:Conic sections]]\n[[Category:Novelty items]]\n[[Category:Educational toys]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Trammel of Archimedes Small White.gif|thumb|Trammel of Archimedes animated model.]]\n\nA '''trammel of Archimedes''' is a [[mechanism (engineering)|mechanism]] that generates the shape of an [[ellipse]].<ref>{{cite book |title=The Words of Mathematics |url=https://archive.org/details/wordsofmathemati0000schw |url-access=registration |last=Schwartzman |first=Steven |year=1996 |publisher=The [[Mathematical Association of America]] |isbn=0-88385-511-9}} ({{Google books|SRw4PevE4zUC|restricted online copy|page=223}})</ref> It consists of two shuttles which are confined (\"[[Wikt:trammel|trammelled]]\") to perpendicular channels or rails and a rod which is attached to the shuttles by pivots at fixed positions along the rod. As the shuttles move back and forth, each along its channel, the end of the rod moves in an elliptical path.  The semi-axes ''a'' and ''b'' of the ellipse have lengths equal to the distances from the end of the rod to each of the two pivots.\n\nAn '''[[ellipsograph]]''' is a trammel of Archimedes intended to draw, cut, or machine ellipses, e.g. in [[wood]] or other sheet materials.  An ellipsograph has the appropriate instrument (pencil, knife, [[wood router|router]], etc.) attached to the rod.  Usually the [[distances]] ''a'' and ''b'' are adjustable, so that the size and shape of the ellipse can be varied.\n\nThe history of such ellipsographs is not certain, but they are believed to date back to [[Proclus]] and perhaps even to the time of [[Archimedes]].<ref name=AMM/>\n\nWooden versions of the trammel of Archimedes have been produced also as [[toy]]s or [[novelty item]]s, and sold under the name of '''[[Kentucky]] do-nothings''', '''nothing grinders''', '''do nothing machines''', or '''bullshit grinders'''.  In these toys  the drafting instrument is replaced by a [[Crank (mechanism)|crank]] handle, and the position of the sliding shuttles is usually fixed.\n\n== Mathematics ==\n{{Gallery\n |align=center\n |title=Concept\n |File:Archimedes Trammel.gif|Trammel of Archimedes as [[ellipsograph]].\n |File:Archimedes Trammel Diagram.png|Diagram]]\n |File:Archimedes_trammel_loci.svg|link={{filepath:Archimedes_trammel_loci.svg}}|Loci of some points along and beyond a trammel of Archimedes, the green \ncircle being the loci of its midpoint &ndash; [{{filepath:Archimedes_trammel_loci.svg}} in the SVG file,] move the pointer over the diagram to move the trammel\n |File:Trammel of Archimedes with three sliders.gif|Trammel of Archimedes with three sliders\n}}\nLet ''C'' be the outer end of the rod, and ''A'', ''B'' be the pivots of the sliders.  Let ''p'' and ''q'' be the distances from ''A'' to ''B'' and ''B'' to ''C'', respectively.  Let us assume that sliders ''A'' and ''B'' move along the ''y'' and ''x'' [[Cartesian coordinates|coordinate]] axes, respectively.  When the rod makes an angle ''\u03b8'' with the ''x''-axis, the coordinates of point ''C'' are given by\n\n:<math>x = (p+q) \\cos\\theta\\,</math>\n:<math>y = q \\sin\\theta\\,</math>\n\nThese are in the form of the standard parametric equations for an ellipse in canonical position. The further equation \n:<math>\\frac{x^2}{(p+q)^2}+ \\frac{y^2}{q^2}= 1</math>\nis immediate as well.\n\nThe trammel of Archimedes is an example of a [[four-bar linkage]] with two sliders and two pivots, and is special case of the more general oblique trammel. The axes constraining the pivots do not have to be perpendicular and the points ''A'', ''B'' and ''C'' can form a triangle. The resulting locus of ''C'' is still an ellipse.<ref name=AMM>{{cite journal|last=Wetzel|first=John E.|title=An Ancient Elliptic Locus|journal=[[American Mathematical Monthly]]|date=February 2010|volume=117|issue=2|pages=161\u2013167|jstor=10|doi=10.4169/000298910x476068}}</ref>\n\n{{Gallery\n |align=center\n |title=Examples of historical devices\n |File:SI ellipsograph crop.jpg|Wooden [[ellipsograph]] (ca. 1900) now at [[Smithsonian Institution Archives|Smithsonian]].\n |File:Bullshit grinder.jpg|Bullshit Grinder (ca. 1960)\n |Ellipse compass-MHS 614-IMG 3827-gradient.jpg|Ellipsograph on display at [[Mus\u00e9e d'histoire des sciences de la Ville de Gen\u00e8ve]].\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Beam compass]]\n* [[Bourke engine]]\n* [[John Farey Jr.]]\n* [[Tusi couple]]\n* [[Useless machine]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* J. W. Downs: ''Practical Conic Sections: The Geometric Properties of Ellipses, Parabolas and Hyperbolas''. Courier Dover 2003, {{ISBN|978-0-486-42876-5}}, pp.&nbsp;4\u20135 ({{Google books|pHxTQTiYkGYC|restricted online copy|page=4}})\n* I. I. Artobolevskii ''Mechanisms for the Generation of Plane Curves''. Pergamon Press 1964, {{ISBN|978-1483120003}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Trammel of Archimedes}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pid70tRkDJo Video of various trammel designs in action]\n*[http://www.woodweb.com/knowledge_base/A_Jig_for_Drawing_or_Cutting_Ellipses.html Cutting ellipses in wood]\n*[https://www.flickr.com/photos/sakraft1/3375895909/ Photo of a Kentucky Do-Nothing]\n*[http://www.instructables.com/id/Do_nothing_Machine/