689-80670-4|year=1996|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref={{SfnRef|Rocco|Rocco|1999}} |title=Dead Reckonings: The Life and Times of the Grateful Dead |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780028648965 |url-access=registration |year=1999 |location=New York |publisher=Schirmer |isbn=978-0-8256-7174-6 |editor1=Rocco, John M. |editor2=Rocco, Brian}}\n* {{cite book|last=Rogatis|first=Jim|title=Milk It!: Collected Musings on the Alternative Music Explosion of the 90s|url=https://books.google.com/?id=LXNUWWuzscMC&pg=PA128|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts|publisher=Da Capo Press|year=2003|isbn=978-0-306-81271-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Roshan|first=Maer|year=2012|location=New York|publisher=[[Sterling Publishing|Sterling]]|title=Courtney Comes Clean: The High Life and Dark Depths of Music's Most Controversial Icon|isbn=978-1-4027-9791-0|series=A Quick Fix Book|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Schippers|first=Mimi A.|title=Rockin' out of the Box: Gender Maneuvering in Alternative Hard Rock|publisher=Rutgers University Press|year=2002|isbn=978-0-8135-3075-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Surmani|first=Karen Farnum|url=https://books.google.com/?id=rwgKbnccWJMC&pg=PA4|series=Basix|isbn=978-0-88284-763-4|year=1997|title=Rock Singing Techniques|location=Van Nuys, California|publisher=Alfred Music|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Yadao|first=Jason S.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8h5oC4SWfC8C&pg=PA54#v=onepage|title=The Rough Guide to Manga|location=New York; London|publisher=Penguin|year=2009|series=Rough Guides|isbn=978-1-85828-561-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite AV media|people=Yapp, Will (dir.)|date=September 26, 2006|title=[[The Return of Courtney Love]]|medium=Documentary|location=Los Angeles|publisher=Channel 4|ref={{sfnref|Yapp|2006}}}}\n* {{cite book|last=Yarm|first=Mark|title=Everybody Loves Our Town: An Oral History of Grunge|isbn=978-0-307-46444-6|location=New York|publisher=Three Rivers Press|year=2011|ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z-44p7V2TrUC&printsec=frontcover}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q222071|b=no|wikt=no|s=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|n=y}}\n* {{Amg name|43419}}\n* {{IMDb name|0001482}}\n* {{curlie|Arts/People/L/Love%2C_Courtney/}}\n* [https://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-no96010504/ Works by or about] Courtney Love (library search via [[WorldCat]])\n\n{{Courtney Love}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Courtney Love|Awards for Courtney Love]]\n| list  =\n{{New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Supporting Actress}}\n{{Satellite Award Best Supporting Actress Motion Picture}}\n}}\n{{Hole}}\n{{Faith No More}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Love, Courtney}}\n[[Category:Courtney Love| ]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American alternative rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Alternative rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American female guitarists]]\n[[Category:American punk rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American female rock singers]]\n[[Category:Alternative rock singers]]\n[[Category:American punk rock singers]]\n[[Category:Female punk rock singers]]\n[[Category:American rock songwriters]]\n[[Category:American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Hole (band) members]]\n[[Category:Faith No More members]]\n[[Category:Sympathy for the Record Industry artists]]\n[[Category:Feminist musicians]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Oregon]]\n[[Category:Singers from Oregon]]\n[[Category:Singers from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Oregon]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Actresses from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:American women painters]]\n[[Category:American contraltos]]\n[[Category:American feminists]]\n[[Category:American people of Cuban descent]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Welsh descent]]\n[[Category:People educated at Nelson College for Girls]]\n[[Category:People from Lane County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Portland State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Squatters]]\n[[Category:Writers from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n", "name_user": "Ss112", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1988\u20131991: Beginnings of Hole", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Courtney_Love"}
{"title_page": "2016 Ogmore by-election", "text_new": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name       = 2016 Ogmore by-election\n| type                = parliamentary\n| country             = Wales\n| seats_for_election  = [[Ogmore (UK Parliament constituency)|Ogmore]] constituency\n| ongoing             = no\n| previous_election   = 2015 United Kingdom general election\n| previous_year       = 2015\n| next_election       = 2017 United Kingdom general election\n| next_year           = 2017\n| election_date       = 5 May 2016\n| candidate1          = '''[[Chris Elmore]]'''\n| image1              = [[File:Official portrait of Chris Elmore crop 2.jpg|110px]]\n| party1              = Labour Party (UK)\n| last_election1      = \n| popular_vote1       = '''12,383'''\n| percentage1         = '''52.6%'''\n| swing1              = {{decrease}}0.3%\n\n| image2              = [[File:No image wide.svg|95x50px|Blank]]\n| candidate2          = Glenda Davies\n| party2              = UK Independence Party\n| last_election2      =  \n| popular_vote2       = 3,808\n| percentage2         = 16.2%\n| swing2              = {{increase}}1.2%\n\n| image4              = [[File:No image wide.svg|95x50px|Blank]]\n| candidate4          = Abi Thomas\n| party4              = Plaid Cymru\n| last_election4      = \n| popular_vote4       = 3,683\n| percentage4         = 15.7%\n| swing4 = {{increase}}5.6%\n\n| image5              =  [[File:No image wide.svg|95x50px|Blank]]\n| candidate5          = Alex Williams\n| party5              = Conservative Party (UK)\n| popular_vote5       = 2,956\n| percentage5         = 12.6%\n| swing5              = {{decrease}}3.3%\n| map_image           = Ogmore2007Constituency.svg\n| map_size            = 250px\n| map_caption         = Location of [[Ogmore (UK Parliament constituency)|Ogmore]] within [[Wales]] \n| title               = [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n| posttitle           = \n| before_election     = [[Huw Irranca-Davies]] \n| before_party        = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| after_election      = [[Chris Elmore]]\n| after_party         = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Ogmore by-election''' was a [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]]ary [[List of United Kingdom by-elections (2010\u2013present)|by-election]] in the constituency of [[Ogmore (UK Parliament constituency)|Ogmore]] in [[Wales]], on 5 May 2016 following the resignation of the incumbent [[Huw Irranca-Davies]] following his decision to contest the coterminous [[Ogmore (Assembly constituency)|Ogmore constituency]] in the Welsh Assembly election.\n\n[[Chris Elmore]] of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] won the by-election with 52.6 percent of the vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://oggybloggyogwr.com/2016/05/ogmore-by-election-result/|title=Ogmore By-Election Result \u2013 Oggy Bloggy Ogwr|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref>\n\nThe by-election was held on the same day as the [[2016 National Assembly for Wales election|2016 Welsh Assembly election]] as well as elections for the [[2016 Scottish Parliament election|Scottish Parliament]], the [[2016 Northern Ireland Assembly election|Northern Ireland Assembly]], for [[2016 London mayoral election|the Mayor]] and [[2016 London Assembly election|Assembly of London]] and in numerous [[2016 United Kingdom local elections|local authorities in England]]. A [[2016 Sheffield Brightside and Hillsborough by-election|by-election for Sheffield Brightside and Hillsborough]] was also held on the same day.\n\n==Background==\nThe seat fell vacant after the incumbent [[Member of Parliament|MP]], [[Huw Irranca-Davies]] of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], chose to resign following his selection to contest the coterminous [[Ogmore (Assembly constituency)|Ogmore constituency]] in the Welsh Assembly election.<ref>{{cite news|title=Labour MP Huw Irranca-Davies selected to fight assembly seat|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-35020417|accessdate=14 February 2016|date=2015-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Casalicchio|first=Emilio|title=Two by-elections set for same day as UK-wide polls|newspaper=PoliticsHome|publisher=[[Dod's Parliamentary Communications]]|date=24 March 2016|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/government-and-public-sector/news/73118/two-elections-set-same-day-uk-wide-polls|accessdate=28 March 2016}}</ref> On 23 March 2016, Irranca-Davies was appointed [[Crown Steward and Bailiff of the Manor of Northstead]] the process by which [[Resignation from the British House of Commons|resignations from the House of Commons]] are permitted.<ref>{{cite web|title=Huw Irranca-Davies resigns as MP for Ogmore|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2016/march/huw-irranca-davies-resigns-as-mp-for-ogmore/|website=parliament.uk|accessdate=1 April 2016}}</ref> Irranca-Davies had been the MP for the seat since a previous [[2002 Ogmore by-election|by-election]] in 2002. Irranca-Davies has originally announced that he would seek Labour's nomination for the Welsh Assembley's Ogmore in October 2015, stating that if he was selected he would resign his Westminster seat.<ref>{{cite news|title=MP Huw Irranca-Davies in Welsh assembly seat bid|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=12 October 2015|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-34502671|accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> Irranca-Davies successfully contested his Assembly election. Irranca-Davies was not obliged to resign upon his nomination, though following the [[Wales Act 2014]], which came into effect during the 2016 Assembly election, he would have had to resign his Westminster seat following his Assembly victory. Given that in both the Assembly and Westminster Ogmore was considered a safe seat for Labour his early resignation allowed the by-election to be held on the same day rather than forcing voters to go to the polls again a few weeks later.\n\n==Candidates==\n[[Bridgend County Borough Council]] published the statement of persons nominated on 8 April 2016. This showed that five candidates that contested the election.<ref>{{cite web|title=Statement of Persons Nominated|url=http://www1.bridgend.gov.uk/media/324919/parliamentary-statement-of-persons-nominated-ogmore.docx|website=Bridgend CBC|accessdate=9 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422212940/http://www1.bridgend.gov.uk/media/324919/parliamentary-statement-of-persons-nominated-ogmore.docx|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nCouncillor [[Chris Elmore]], currently Cabinet Member for Children's Services and Schools in the [[Vale of Glamorgan Council]], represented Labour.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/wales/update/2016-02-13/elmore-selected-as-labour-candidate-in-ogmore-by-election/ |title=Elmore selected as Labour candidate in Ogmore by-election &#124; Wales - ITV News |publisher=Itv.com |date=2016-02-13 |accessdate=2016-05-19}}</ref> Elmore contested the [[Vale of Glamorgan (UK Parliament constituency)|Vale of Glamorgan]] constituency in [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], where he lost to the [[Welsh Conservative Party|Conservatives]].\n\nThe [[Welsh Conservative Party|Conservatives]] selected Alex Williams, a town councillor in Ogmore. Glenda Davies was the candidate for [[UKIP]], she also stood for the seat at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]]. She was the [[UKIP]]'s candidate for the [[Aberavon (Assembly constituency)|Aberavon]] constituency in the [[2016 National Assembly for Wales election|Welsh Assembly election]] held on the same day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ukip.wales/2016-candidates |title=Archived copy |accessdate=April 28, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420120759/http://ukip.wales/2016-candidates/ |archivedate=April 20, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nAbi Thomas stood for [[Plaid Cymru]]. The Liberal Democrats selected Janet Ellard, a former teacher and now volunteer manager for a youth homeless charity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freedomcentral.org.uk/2016/03/ogmore-by-election-welsh-liberal-democrats-announce-candidate.html |title=OGMORE BY-ELECTION: Welsh Liberal Democrats announce candidate \u2013 Freedom Central |publisher=Freedomcentral.org.uk |date=2016-03-24 |accessdate=2016-05-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503211852/http://www.freedomcentral.org.uk/2016/03/ogmore-by-election-welsh-liberal-democrats-announce-candidate.html |archive-date=2016-05-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe incumbent party (Labour) selected Chris Elmore as their candidate; Elmore prevailed in the election, winning the seat.<ref>{{cite web|title=Elmore selected as Labour candidate in Ogmore by-election|url=http://www.itv.com/news/wales/update/2016-02-13/elmore-selected-as-labour-candidate-in-ogmore-by-election|website=ITV News|accessdate=15 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin|title=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|General election 2015]]: Ogmore<ref name=electoralcalculus2015>{{cite web|title=Election Data 2015|url=http://www.electoralcalculus.co.uk/electdata_2015.txt|publisher=[[Electoral Calculus]]|accessdate=17 October 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017112223/http://www.electoralcalculus.co.uk/electdata_2015.txt|archivedate=17 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Bridgend and Ogmore results\">{{cite web|title=Bridgend and Ogmore results|url=http://www1.bridgend.gov.uk/services/electoral-services/elections.aspx|website=Elections|publisher=Bridgend County Borough Council|accessdate=21 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923060422/http://www1.bridgend.gov.uk/services/electoral-services/elections.aspx|archive-date=23 September 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/W07000074|accessdate=27 April 2015|title=Ogmore parliamentary constituency - Election 2017}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[Huw Irranca-Davies]]\n  |votes      = 18,663\n  |percentage = 52.9\n  |change     = \u22120.9\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Jane March\n  |votes      = 5,620\n  |percentage = 15.9\n  |change     = +0.3\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = UK Independence Party\n  |candidate  = Glenda Davies\n  |votes      = 5,420\n  |percentage = 15.4\n  |change     = +13.1\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Plaid Cymru\n  |candidate  = Tim Thomas\n  |votes      = 3,556\n  |percentage = 10.1\n  |change     = +0.5\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n  |candidate  = Gerald Francis<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libdems.org.uk/general_election_candidates#South |title=Archived copy |accessdate=19 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150219212032/http://www.libdems.org.uk/general_election_candidates |archivedate=19 February 2015 }} West</ref>\n  |votes      = 1,072\n  |percentage = 3.0\n  |change     = \u221212.1\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Green Party of England and Wales\n  |candidate  = Laurie Brophy\n  |votes      = 754\n  |percentage = 2.1\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Trade Unionist and Socialist Coalition\n  |candidate  = Emma Saunders\n  |votes      = 165\n  |percentage = 0.5\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      = 13,043\n  |percentage = 37.0\n  |change     = \u22121.2\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      = 35,250\n  |percentage = 63.7\n  |change     = +1.3\n}}\n{{Election box registered electors|\n  |reg. electors = 55,572\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n  |winner     = Labour Party (UK)\n  |swing      = \u22120.6\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Result==\n{{Election box begin |title=[[2016 Ogmore by-election]]<ref>{{cite news | title = Labour MP quits Commons to run for seat in Cardiff Bay | publisher = [[BBC News Online]] | date = 2016-03-23 | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-35885206 | access-date = 2016-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Casalicchio | first = Emilio  | title = Two by-elections set for same day as UK-wide polls | newspaper = PoliticsHome | publisher = [[Dod's Parliamentary Communications]] | date = 2016-03-24 | url = https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/government-and-public-sector/news/73118/two-elections-set-same-day-uk-wide-polls | access-date = 2016-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://researchbriefings.files.parliament.uk/documents/CBP-7417/CBP-7417.pdf|title=By-election results since the 2015 General Election|access-date=2020-02-14|website=House of Commons Library}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[Chris Elmore]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.itv.com/news/wales/update/2016-02-13/elmore-selected-as-labour-candidate-in-ogmore-by-election/ |title = Elmore selected as Labour candidate in Ogmore by-election}}</ref>\n  |votes      = 12,383\n  |percentage = 52.6\n  |change     = -0.3\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = UK Independence Party\n  |candidate  = Glenda Davies\n  |votes      = 3,808\n  |percentage = 16.2\n  |change     = +1.2\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Plaid Cymru\n  |candidate  = Abi Thomas\n  |votes      = 3,683\n  |percentage = 15.7\n  |change     = +5.6\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Alex Williams\n  |votes      = 2,956\n  |percentage = 12.6\n  |change     = -3.3\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n  |candidate  = Janet Ellard\n  |votes      = 702\n  |percentage = 3.0\n  |change     = \u00b10.0\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      = 8,575\n  |percentage = 36.4\n  |change     = -0.6\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      = 23,532\n  |percentage = 43.0\n  |change     = -20.7\n}}\n{{Election box registered electors|\n  |reg. electors = 55,027\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n  |winner     = Labour Party (UK)\n  |swing      = -0.8\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[1931 Ogmore by-election]]\n* [[1946 Ogmore by-election]]\n* [[2002 Ogmore by-election]]\n* [[List of United Kingdom by-elections (2010\u2013present)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{By-elections to the 56th UK Parliament}}\n{{Westminster by-elections in Wales 1950\u2013present}}\n\n[[Category:2016 elections in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:By-elections to the Parliament of the United Kingdom in Welsh constituencies]]\n[[Category:May 2016 events in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name       = 2016 Ogmore by-election\n| type                = parliamentary\n| country             = Wales\n| seats_for_election  = [[Ogmore (UK Parliament constituency)|Ogmore]] constituency\n| ongoing             = no\n| previous_election   = 2015 United Kingdom general election\n| previous_year       = 2015\n| next_election       = 2017 United Kingdom general election\n| next_year           = 2017\n| election_date       = 5 May 2016\n| candidate1          = '''[[Chris Elmore]]'''\n| image1              = [[File:Official portrait of Chris Elmore crop 2.jpg|110px]]\n| party1              = Labour Party (UK)\n| last_election1      = \n| popular_vote1       = '''12,383'''\n| percentage1         = '''52.6%'''\n| swing1 = {{decrease}}0.3%\n\n| image2              = [[File:No image wide.svg|95x50px|Blank]]\n| candidate2          =Glenda Davies\n| party2              = UK Independence Party\n| last_election2      =  \n| popular_vote2       = 3,808\n| percentage2         = 16.2%\n| swing2 = {{increase}}1.2%\n\n| image4             = [[File:No image wide.svg|95x50px|Blank]]\n| candidate4          = Abi Thomas\n| party4              = Plaid Cymru\n| last_election4      = \n| popular_vote4       = 3,683\n| percentage4         = 15.7%\n| swing4 = {{increase}}5.6%\n\n| image5              =  [[File:No image wide.svg|95x50px|Blank]]\n| candidate5          = Alex Williams\n| party5              = Conservative Party (UK)\n| popular_vote5       = 2,956\n| percentage5         = 12.6%\n| swing5 = {{decrease}}3.3%\n| map_image           = Ogmore2007Constituency.svg\n| map_size            = 250px\n| map_caption         = Location of [[Ogmore (UK Parliament constituency)|Ogmore]] within [[Wales]] \n| title               = [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n| posttitle           = \n| before_election     = [[Huw Irranca-Davies]] \n| before_party        = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| after_election      = [[Chris Elmore]]\n| after_party         = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Ogmore by-election''' was a [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]]ary [[List of United Kingdom by-elections (2010\u2013present)|by-election]] in the constituency of [[Ogmore (UK Parliament constituency)|Ogmore]] in [[Wales]], on 5 May 2016 following the resignation of the incumbent [[Huw Irranca-Davies]] following his decision to contest the coterminous [[Ogmore (Assembly constituency)|Ogmore constituency]] in the Welsh Assembly election.\n\n[[Chris Elmore]] of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] won the by-election with 52.6 percent of the vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://oggybloggyogwr.com/2016/05/ogmore-by-election-result/|title=Ogmore By-Election Result \u2013 Oggy Bloggy Ogwr|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref>\n\nThe by-election was held on the same day as the [[2016 National Assembly for Wales election|2016 Welsh Assembly election]] as well as elections for the [[2016 Scottish Parliament election|Scottish Parliament]], the [[2016 Northern Ireland Assembly election|Northern Ireland Assembly]], for [[2016 London mayoral election|the Mayor]] and [[2016 London Assembly election|Assembly of London]] and in numerous [[2016 United Kingdom local elections|local authorities in England]]. A [[2016 Sheffield Brightside and Hillsborough by-election|by-election for Sheffield Brightside and Hillsborough]] was also held on the same day.\n\n==Background==\nThe seat fell vacant after the incumbent [[Member of Parliament|MP]], [[Huw Irranca-Davies]] of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], chose to resign following his selection to contest the coterminous [[Ogmore (Assembly constituency)|Ogmore constituency]] in the Welsh Assembly election.<ref>{{cite news|title=Labour MP Huw Irranca-Davies selected to fight assembly seat|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-35020417|accessdate=14 February 2016|date=2015-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Casalicchio|first=Emilio|title=Two by-elections set for same day as UK-wide polls|newspaper=PoliticsHome|publisher=[[Dod's Parliamentary Communications]]|date=24 March 2016|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/government-and-public-sector/news/73118/two-elections-set-same-day-uk-wide-polls|accessdate=28 March 2016}}</ref> On 23 March 2016, Irranca-Davies was appointed [[Crown Steward and Bailiff of the Manor of Northstead]] the process by which [[Resignation from the British House of Commons|resignations from the House of Commons]] are permitted.<ref>{{cite web|title=Huw Irranca-Davies resigns as MP for Ogmore|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2016/march/huw-irranca-davies-resigns-as-mp-for-ogmore/|website=parliament.uk|accessdate=1 April 2016}}</ref> Irranca-Davies had been the MP for the seat since a previous [[2002 Ogmore by-election|by-election]] in 2002. Irranca-Davies has originally announced that he would seek Labour's nomination for the Welsh Assembley's Ogmore in October 2015, stating that if he was selected he would resign his Westminster seat.<ref>{{cite news|title=MP Huw Irranca-Davies in Welsh assembly seat bid|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=12 October 2015|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-34502671|accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> Irranca-Davies successfully contested his Assembly election. Irranca-Davies was not obliged to resign upon his nomination, though following the [[Wales Act 2014]], which came into effect during the 2016 Assembly election, he would have had to resign his Westminster seat following his Assembly victory. Given that in both the Assembly and Westminster Ogmore was considered a safe seat for Labour his early resignation allowed the by-election to be held on the same day rather than forcing voters to go to the polls again a few weeks later.\n\n==Candidates==\n[[Bridgend County Borough Council]] published the statement of persons nominated on 8 April 2016. This showed that five candidates that contested the election.<ref>{{cite web|title=Statement of Persons Nominated|url=http://www1.bridgend.gov.uk/media/324919/parliamentary-statement-of-persons-nominated-ogmore.docx|website=Bridgend CBC|accessdate=9 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422212940/http://www1.bridgend.gov.uk/media/324919/parliamentary-statement-of-persons-nominated-ogmore.docx|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nCouncillor [[Chris Elmore]], currently Cabinet Member for Children's Services and Schools in the [[Vale of Glamorgan Council]], represented Labour.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/wales/update/2016-02-13/elmore-selected-as-labour-candidate-in-ogmore-by-election/ |title=Elmore selected as Labour candidate in Ogmore by-election &#124; Wales - ITV News |publisher=Itv.com |date=2016-02-13 |accessdate=2016-05-19}}</ref> Elmore contested the [[Vale of Glamorgan (UK Parliament constituency)|Vale of Glamorgan]] constituency in [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], where he lost to the [[Welsh Conservative Party|Conservatives]].\n\nThe [[Welsh Conservative Party|Conservatives]] selected Alex Williams, a town councillor in Ogmore. Glenda Davies was the candidate for [[UKIP]], she also stood for the seat at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]]. She was the [[UKIP]]'s candidate for the [[Aberavon (Assembly constituency)|Aberavon]] constituency in the [[2016 National Assembly for Wales election|Welsh Assembly election]] held on the same day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ukip.wales/2016-candidates |title=Archived copy |accessdate=April 28, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420120759/http://ukip.wales/2016-candidates/ |archivedate=April 20, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nAbi Thomas stood for [[Plaid Cymru]]. The Liberal Democrats selected Janet Ellard, a former teacher and now volunteer manager for a youth homeless charity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freedomcentral.org.uk/2016/03/ogmore-by-election-welsh-liberal-democrats-announce-candidate.html |title=OGMORE BY-ELECTION: Welsh Liberal Democrats announce candidate \u2013 Freedom Central |publisher=Freedomcentral.org.uk |date=2016-03-24 |accessdate=2016-05-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503211852/http://www.freedomcentral.org.uk/2016/03/ogmore-by-election-welsh-liberal-democrats-announce-candidate.html |archive-date=2016-05-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe incumbent party (Labour) selected Chris Elmore as their candidate; Elmore prevailed in the election, winning the seat.<ref>{{cite web|title=Elmore selected as Labour candidate in Ogmore by-election|url=http://www.itv.com/news/wales/update/2016-02-13/elmore-selected-as-labour-candidate-in-ogmore-by-election|website=ITV News|accessdate=15 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin|title=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|General election 2015]]: Ogmore<ref name=electoralcalculus2015>{{cite web|title=Election Data 2015|url=http://www.electoralcalculus.co.uk/electdata_2015.txt|publisher=[[Electoral Calculus]]|accessdate=17 October 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017112223/http://www.